{{nihongo|'''''Tutankham'''''|ツタンカーム|Tsutankāmu}} is a 1982 [[arcade video game]] developed and released by [[Konami]]<ref name="CVG"/><ref name="Retro"/> and released by [[Stern (game company)|Stern]] in North America.<ref name="GM194">{{cite magazine|title=Overseas Readers Column - Konami And Stern Pact On "Tutankham" Video|magazine=[[:ja:ゲームマシン|Game Machine]]|issue=194|publisher=[[:ja:アミューズメント通信社|Amusement Press, Inc.]]|date=15 August 1982|page=26|lang=ja|url=https://onitama.tv/gamemachine/pdf/19820815p.pdf}}</ref> Named after the Egyptian [[pharaoh]] [[Tutankhamun]],<ref name="Retro"/> the game combines a [[List of maze video games|maze]] [[shoot 'em up]] with light [[Puzzle video game|puzzle-solving]] elements.<ref name="CVG"/><ref name="Weiss"/><ref name="Video"/> It debuted at the European [[Amusement Trades Exhibition International|ATE]] and IMA amusement shows in [[1982 in video games|January 1982]],<ref name="GM194"/><ref name="CVG"/> before releasing worldwide in Summer 1982. The game was a critical and commercial success and was ported to home systems by [[Parker Brothers]].

Armed with a [[laser weapon]] that only fires horizontally, the player loots the maze-like Egyptian [[tomb of Tutankhamun]] while finding keys to locked chambers and fighting off creatures. ''Tutankham'' is one of six games in a group photograph published in the January 1983 issue ''[[Life (magazine)|LIFE]]'' along with the record holder for each.  The ''Tutankham'' champion in the photo is Mark Robichek of [[Mountain View, California]].

==Gameplay==
Taking on the role of an explorer [[grave robbing]] the maze-like [[Tomb of Tutankhamun|tomb]] of Egyptian [[pharaoh]] [[Tutankhamun]],<ref name="phosphor">{{cite web |url=http://www.thelogbook.com/phosphor/1983/tutankham-o2/ |title=Tutankham |date= |website=www.thelogbook.com |access-date=2017-03-09 |archive-date=2017-03-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170312033350/http://www.thelogbook.com/phosphor/1983/tutankham-o2/ |url-status=dead}}</ref> the player is chased by [[Asp (reptile)|asps]], [[vultures]], [[parrots]], [[bat]]s, [[dragons]], and [[curse]]s, all of which kill the explorer on contact. The explorer wields a laser weapon that only fires left and right—there is no vertical offense—as well as a single screen-clearing "flash bomb" per level or life. Warp zones teleport the player to another location in the level, which enemies cannot use.

To progress, the player collects keys to open locked doors throughout each level and well as optional treasures for bonus points. The player can only carry one key at a time, so the game requires backtracking through an area in order to acquire a second key.<ref name="HG101">{{cite web |last1=Kalata |first1=Kurt |title=Tutankham |url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/tutankham/ |access-date=20 May 2021 |website=Hardcore Gaming 101 |date=April 14, 2020}}</ref> When a timer reaches zero the explorer can no longer shoot. Passing through the large exit door ends the level, and any remaining time is converted to bonus points.

Extra life is given at 30,000, and none more thereafter. The hero dies upon touching any enemy or spark. Play continues to the last hero dead, which ends the game.

==Ports==
''Tutankham'' was ported to home systems by [[Parker Brothers]], who advertised the game extensively in North America,<ref name="HG101"/><ref name="eg_16">{{cite magazine|title=Tutankham: The Home Video Game You've Waited 3000 Years For|magazine=[[Electronic Games]]|date=June 1983|volume=4|issue=16|url=https://archive.org/details/Electronic_Games_Volume_01_Number_16_1983-06_Reese_Communications_US/page/n10|page=11}}</ref> where it released in June 1983.<ref name="eg_16"/> It was ported to the [[Atari 2600]], [[ColecoVision]], [[Intellivision]], [[VIC-20]], [[PV-1000]], and [[PC-6001]]. Versions for the [[Odyssey²]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Odyssey2 |website=the-nextlevel.com |url=http://www.the-nextlevel.com/odyssey2/db/game.php?gameid=132 |accessdate=March 16, 2015}}</ref> [[TI-99/4A]],<ref>{{cite web |title=TI-99/4A Prototype Cartridge |url=http://videogamehouse.net/prototypes/tutankham/ |website=TI-99/4A Videogame House}}</ref> and [[Atari 8-bit computers]]<ref>{{cite web |last=Reichert |first=Matt |title=Atari |website=AtariProtos.com |url=http://www.atariprotos.com/8bit/software/tutankham/tutankham.htm |accessdate=September 19, 2014}}</ref> were in development by Parker Brothers in 1983, but not published.

Two tabletop versions of ''Tutankham'' were released: an [[Liquid-crystal display|LCD]] game in Japan and Europe from [[Bandai]] resembling an [[Arcade cabinet#Cocktail or table cabinets|cocktail arcade cabinet]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Bandai Tutankham (LCD) |url=https://www.handheldmuseum.com/Bandai/TutankhamLCD.htm |website=Handheld Museum}}</ref> and a [[Vacuum fluorescent display|VFD]] game from Bandai in Japan and Konami in North America.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bandai Tutankham (VFD) |url=https://handheldmuseum.com/Bandai/Tutankham.htm |website=Handheld Museum}}</ref>

In May 2024, [[Hamster Corporation|Hamster]] released ''Tutankham'' as part of the [[Arcade Archives]] series for the Nintendo Switch. 
<ref>{{cite web |title=Nintendo Tutankham |url=https://www.nintendo.com/us/store/products/arcade-archives-tutankham-switch/ |website=Nintendo}}</ref>

